Key Insights & Analysis

  • Health Impact: Average of 0.5 estimated respiratory cases per day
  • Pollution Levels: PM2.5 average of 23.4 µg/m³ (exceeds WHO guidelines)
  • Primary Correlate: PM10 (ug/m3) shows strongest correlation (r = 0.073)
  • Data Quality: 100.0% complete

Key Characteristics

  • SEVERE PEDIATRIC CRISIS (59.1% under-5 ARI - highest child burden!)
  • French colonial healthcare legacy (JIPMER excellence). Union territory advantages (high per capita income). Coastal climate benefits
  • Multiple seasonal virus patterns (not just winter peaks). Pediatric respiratory emergency despite excellent healthcare
  • Puducherry demonstrates how excellent healthcare and high income can coexist with severe pediatric respiratory challenges
    •

    *Synthetic Data Considerations

  • Population: ~1.7M (territory), ~950K (city); literacy 85.85%; sex ratio 1038/1000; majority Hindu population
  • Respiratory Disease: Acute respiratory infection 59.1% (under-5 children); influenza A/H1N1 16.8%, RSV 5.2%, influenza B 6.5%; winter seasonal peaks; ARI deaths peaked at 87 (2012)
  • Healthcare: JIPMER (2,135 beds), 137 government hospitals, 222+ private hospitals; comprehensive network serving 55 lakh outpatients, 1.5 lakh inpatients annually; per capita health expenditure ₹1,658
  • Seasonal Patterns: Respiratory infections surge in winter (Dec-Feb) and rainy season (Aug-Jan); RSV peaks during monsoon, HMPV and PIV-3 peak in summer (April-May)
  • Socioeconomic: Per capita income ₹3,02,680 (2024-25); urban density 3,232/sq km; 14% urban population in slums (1.18 lakh people); economic growth 9.56% annually
